When you schedule a send with `raise(event, { id, delay })` or `sendTo(ref, event, { id, delay })`, v5 stores the timer under that `id`. The timer fires unless you explicitly invalidate it with the `cancel(id)` action before the delay elapses. Cancellation is idempotent: calling `cancel` when nothing is scheduled is a no-op. Scheduled sends are also cleaned up automatically when the state that scheduled them is exited, so the common explicit-cancel pattern is "a sibling transition took us elsewhere before the timer fired".

